description: From Middle English wange, from Old English wange (“jaw, cheek”), from Proto-Germanic *wangô (“cheek”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenk-, *wek- (“to be bent or bowed”). Cognate with Scots wan, wang (“cheek”), West Frisian wang (“cheek”), Dutch wang (“cheek”), German Wange (“cheek”), Icelandic vanga (“cheek”), Gothic *𐍅𐌰𐌲𐌲𐍉 (*waggō) in 𐍅𐌰𐌲𐌲𐌰𐍂𐌴𐌹𐍃 (waggareis, “pillow, cushion”), Italian guancia (“cheek”).

entries.meaning: (dialectal or obsolete) The cheek; the jaw.
To continue to talk about a specific subject.

verbs.description: wang (third-person singular simple present wangs, present participle wanging, simple past and past participle wanged)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To batter; to clobber; to conk.

description: Uncertain. Perhaps short for whangdoodle (“gadget, doodad”), or from whang (“stour, thick slice", also "thong”), from thwang (“thong”). See thong.

examples: Montana was naked, and so was Billy, of course. He had a tremendous wang, incidentally. You never know who’ll get one.
